COLMAP / Gaussian Splatting Prep Setup
=====================================

This project prepares an image folder or video for COLMAP and Gaussian
Splatting-style training.

The main Windows script is:

    prepare_colmap_windows.py

It runs:

    1. Copy images or extract video frames
    2. COLMAP feature extraction
    3. COLMAP matching
    4. COLMAP mapper
    5. COLMAP image undistortion
    6. Optional sparse PLY export


Requirements
============

Required:

    Python 3.10+
    COLMAP for Windows

Required only for video input:

    FFmpeg

Python packages:

    None are required by the current scripts.

You do not need a Python virtual environment for the current scripts, because
they only use the Python standard library and external programs.


Install COLMAP
==============

Download COLMAP for Windows and unzip it.

This script checks these paths automatically:

    C:\Users\login\Downloads\colmap-x64-windows-cuda\COLMAP.bat
    C:\Users\login\Downloads\colmap-x64-windows-cuda\bin\colmap.exe
    C:\Program Files\COLMAP\COLMAP.bat
    C:\Program Files\COLMAP\bin\colmap.exe

If COLMAP is somewhere else, pass it manually:

    python prepare_colmap_windows.py data output --colmap "C:\path\to\COLMAP.bat" --overwrite --export-ply

To check COLMAP GUI:

    "C:\Users\login\Downloads\colmap-x64-windows-cuda\COLMAP.bat" gui


Install FFmpeg For Videos
=========================

FFmpeg is only needed when your input is a video file.

Recommended Windows install:

    winget install --id Gyan.FFmpeg -e

After installing, close and reopen PowerShell, then check:

    ffmpeg -version

If you do not install FFmpeg, you can still use the script with an image folder.

Run On Image Folder
===================

From the project folder:

    python prepare_colmap_windows.py data output --overwrite --export-ply

For the small test folder:

    python prepare_colmap_windows.py data_test output_data_test --overwrite --export-ply


Run On Video
============

Example:

    python prepare_colmap_windows.py clip.mp4 output_video --fps 2 --overwrite --export-ply

Video options:

    --fps 2
        Extracts 2 frames per second.

    --frame-width 1600
        Optional. Resizes extracted video frames to 1600 pixels wide.
        If omitted, extracted frames keep the original video size.

Supported video extensions:

    .mp4
    .mov
    .avi
    .mkv
    .webm


Useful Options
==============

    --overwrite
        Deletes and recreates the output folder.

    --export-ply
        Exports a sparse COLMAP point cloud:

            output\sparse_points.ply

    --matcher sequential
        Good for ordered video frames. This is the default.

    --matcher exhaustive
        Better for unordered photos, but slower.

    --camera-model OPENCV
        Default camera model used by the script.


Output Structure
================

After a successful run, the output folder should contain:

    output\input
        Original copied images or extracted video frames.

    output\distorted\database.db
        COLMAP database.

    output\distorted\sparse
        Original COLMAP sparse reconstruction models.

    output\images
        Undistorted images for registered frames.

    output\sparse\0
        Final sparse model in the layout expected by Gaussian Splatting.

    output\sparse_points.ply
        Optional sparse PLY if --export-ply was used.


Open In COLMAP GUI
==================

To view the final reconstruction, open:

    output\sparse\0

If COLMAP asks:

    Directory does not contain a project.ini...

Click:

    No

That means "only visualize the reconstruction".

Click Yes only if you want to resume reconstruction and provide:

    Database:
        output\distorted\database.db

    Images:
        output\input


Notes On Sparse Results
=======================

COLMAP will not always register every input image.

For example, 700 input frames does not mean 700 registered frames. COLMAP only
keeps images it can connect with enough reliable geometric matches.

If the model has very few frames or points:

    - Use sharper images.
    - Use higher resolution input.
    - Add more side-to-side camera movement, not only forward motion.
    - Improve lighting.
    - Avoid blur and reflections.
    - Add visible texture to plain surfaces if possible.
    - Try --matcher exhaustive for unordered photos.

For dense point clouds, run COLMAP dense stereo after sparse reconstruction:

    patch_match_stereo
    stereo_fusion

The sparse model is only feature points; it is not supposed to be a full dense
surface by itself.
